Running an Ansible playbook using Podman is a common approach in containerized or disconnected environments (like your OpenShift setups). I’ll walk you through the simplest and most practical ways.


---

✅ 1. Use a Prebuilt Ansible Container Image

You don’t need to install Ansible locally—just run it inside a container.

Example (quick run)

podman run --rm -it \
  -v $(pwd):/workspace \
  -w /workspace \
  docker.io/ansible/ansible-runner \
  ansible-playbook playbook.yml

🔹 Explanation:

--rm → remove container after execution

-it → interactive terminal

-v $(pwd):/workspace → mount your current directory

-w /workspace → set working directory

ansible-playbook playbook.yml → runs your script



---

✅ 2. Pass Inventory File

If you have an inventory file:

podman run --rm -it \
  -v $(pwd):/workspace \
  -w /workspace \
  docker.io/ansible/ansible-runner \
  ansible-playbook -i inventory.ini playbook.yml


---

✅ 3. SSH Keys / Credentials (Important ⚠️)

If your playbook connects to remote hosts:

podman run --rm -it \
  -v $(pwd):/workspace \
  -v ~/.ssh:/root/.ssh:Z \
  -w /workspace \
  docker.io/ansible/ansible-runner \
  ansible-playbook -i inventory.ini playbook.yml

👉 :Z is important for SELinux systems (like RHEL/OpenShift nodes).


---

✅ 4. Using Custom Ansible Image (Recommended for OCP)

You can build your own container with required collections:

Dockerfile (Podman works with it)

FROM quay.io/ansible/ansible-runner

RUN ansible-galaxy collection install community.general

Build image

podman build -t my-ansible .

Run it

podman run --rm -it \
  -v $(pwd):/workspace \
  -w /workspace \
  my-ansible \
  ansible-playbook playbook.yml


---

✅ 5. Passing Extra Variables

ansible-playbook playbook.yml -e "env=prod"

Inside Podman:

podman run --rm -it \
  -v $(pwd):/workspace \
  -w /workspace \
  docker.io/ansible/ansible-runner \
  ansible-playbook playbook.yml -e "env=prod"


---

✅ 6. Environment Variables (Proxy / Registry / OCP cases)

podman run --rm -it \
  -e HTTP_PROXY=http://proxy:8080 \
  -e HTTPS_PROXY=http://proxy:8080 \
  -v $(pwd):/workspace \
  -w /workspace \
  docker.io/ansible/ansible-runner \
  ansible-playbook playbook.yml


---

✅ 7. Debug Mode

ansible-playbook -vvv playbook.yml


---

🔥 Pro Tips (Based on Your OCP Work)

Since you're working with disconnected OpenShift:

Use a local registry image instead of Docker Hub

Pre-load collections inside container

Mount kubeconfig if needed:


-v ~/.kube:/root/.kube:Z


---

🚀 Summary

You basically need:

podman run \
  -v <your-code>:/workspace \
  <ansible-image> \
  ansible-playbook <playbook>


